1
00:01:23,958 --> 00:01:24,958
Hey, Rick.

2
00:01:26,250 --> 00:01:28,250
Hi. I made it.

3
00:01:30,291 --> 00:01:31,708
Phillip.

4
00:01:44,208 --> 00:01:45,750
The culprit is here.

5
00:01:46,458 --> 00:01:47,833
We must capture him.

6
00:01:49,041 --> 00:01:50,333
We must capture him.

7
00:01:51,416 --> 00:01:53,166
That is our challenge.

8
00:02:25,166 --> 00:02:26,366
How did you know?

9
00:02:26,916 --> 00:02:28,166
Your face.

10
00:04:32,250 --> 00:04:33,833
Yeah?

11
00:04:33,916 --> 00:04:35,791
<i>I hope you have</i>
<i>a clean black suit.</i>

12
00:04:35,875 --> 00:04:36,875
Morning, Sonia.

13
00:04:36,916 --> 00:04:39,333
<i>I got you a gig today</i>
<i>at 10:00 a.m. in Saitama.</i>

14
00:04:39,416 --> 00:04:41,625
<i>I know it's kinda far,
but can you make it?</i>

15
00:04:41,708 --> 00:04:43,583
Of course.
What's the production?

16
00:04:43,666 --> 00:04:45,125
<i>They didn't give us
too many details,</i>

17
00:04:45,208 --> 00:04:46,500
<i>but pays pretty well.</i>

18
00:04:46,583 --> 00:04:48,875
- What's my role?
<i>- Sad American.</i>

19
00:06:01,583 --> 00:06:03,916
The fuck?

20
00:08:07,458 --> 00:08:09,166
Guess that means
no zombies.

21
00:08:09,250 --> 00:08:10,250
Nope.

22
00:08:17,708 --> 00:08:19,791
Anyway, you've got 15 minutes.

23
00:08:19,875 --> 00:08:21,166
Until what?

24
00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:24,500
The next guest will arrive.
And he won't be getting up.

25
00:08:43,333 --> 00:08:45,000
Nothing about that was fake.

26
00:08:45,083 --> 00:08:47,625
Especially to Mr. Daito.
The man in the box.

27
00:08:47,708 --> 00:08:49,458
Well, what would you call it,
then?

28
00:09:01,166 --> 00:09:02,166
You know?

29
00:09:07,916 --> 00:09:09,517
I might be able
to use you for something

30
00:09:09,541 --> 00:09:11,750
more than a sad American.

31
00:09:12,750 --> 00:09:13,958
All right.

32
00:10:11,541 --> 00:10:12,767
I knew you would come.

33
00:10:22,666 --> 00:10:24,583
So what do you think we do?

34
00:10:25,583 --> 00:10:28,500
You, if I have to guess

35
00:10:28,583 --> 00:10:29,916
you, um

36
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,416
you sell people.

37
00:10:33,708 --> 00:10:35,791
- No.
- No.

38
00:10:35,875 --> 00:10:37,125
We sell emotion.

39
00:10:37,208 --> 00:10:38,541
Oh.

40
00:10:38,625 --> 00:10:39,625
How?

41
00:10:39,708 --> 00:10:41,708
We play roles
in the clients' lives.

42
00:10:42,250 --> 00:10:43,583
Thanks.

43
00:10:43,666 --> 00:10:46,833
But...
you can't just,

44
00:10:46,916 --> 00:10:48,583
you know,
replace someone in your life.

45
00:10:48,666 --> 00:10:49,916
Yes and no.

46
00:10:50,958 --> 00:10:52,541
But people are willing
to take a leap.

47
00:10:53,500 --> 00:10:55,166
The actor, the surrogate.

48
00:10:56,208 --> 00:10:57,875
You don't have to be
that person.

49
00:10:57,958 --> 00:11:00,916
You just have to help clients
connect to what's missing.

50
00:11:02,041 --> 00:11:02,875
- Like what?
- Well,

51
00:11:02,958 --> 00:11:04,375
could be anybody
from their life.

52
00:11:04,458 --> 00:11:07,041
Or a feeling they once had.

53
00:11:07,583 --> 00:11:10,666
Parents, siblings, boyfriends,
girlfriends, best friends.

54
00:11:10,750 --> 00:11:12,166
We play it all.

55
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,666
Well, they could just
get a therapist.

56
00:11:15,291 --> 00:11:16,625
It's not that easy here.

57
00:11:17,250 --> 00:11:20,333
Mental health issues are
stigmatized in this country.

58
00:11:20,916 --> 00:11:24,416
So people have to turn
to other things.

59
00:11:24,500 --> 00:11:25,833
Like us.

60
00:11:25,916 --> 00:11:29,125
Well, what do you need me for?

61
00:11:29,791 --> 00:11:31,333
We need a token white guy.

62
00:11:32,666 --> 00:11:33,916
It's a niche market.

63
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,083
And I need someone
to fill the role.

64
00:11:36,625 --> 00:11:38,458
Just token white guy.

65
00:11:39,125 --> 00:11:41,625
Um, I'm... I'm just an actor.

66
00:11:41,708 --> 00:11:42,948
I don't know how to help people.

67
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:44,708
But you know how to perform.

68
00:11:44,791 --> 00:11:46,208
I've seen the résumé.

69
00:11:47,250 --> 00:11:49,875
Look, what I'm offering here

70
00:11:49,958 --> 00:11:52,250
is a chance to play roles
with real meaning.

71
00:12:00,666 --> 00:12:02,625
Thank you so much.

72
00:12:02,708 --> 00:12:06,083
I really appreciate it.
It was nice...

73
00:12:06,166 --> 00:12:07,333
Nice meeting you.

74
00:12:14,625 --> 00:12:15,625
Eh?

75
00:12:16,583 --> 00:12:18,083
Huh?

76
00:12:49,833 --> 00:12:50,892
Nice to meet you.

77
00:12:50,916 --> 00:12:52,101
- How you doing?
- I like this commercial.

78
00:12:52,125 --> 00:12:53,791
- Thanks.
- How long ago was that?

79
00:12:54,333 --> 00:12:55,416
Seven years?

80
00:12:56,583 --> 00:12:58,750
That's what brought you
to Japan, right?

81
00:13:00,333 --> 00:13:04,541
Well, I'm sure you have plenty
of acting gigs to go back to.

82
00:13:05,875 --> 00:13:08,500
Or you can give this a try.

83
00:13:41,250 --> 00:13:42,690
Because you are Canadian

84
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:44,166
and you got a job at home.

85
00:13:44,250 --> 00:13:45,583
Here. Your name is
Brian Callahan.

86
00:13:45,666 --> 00:13:46,666
Okay.

87
00:13:52,083 --> 00:13:56,208
Are you sure
that I'm not too old for you?

88
00:13:56,750 --> 00:13:57,750
No.

89
00:13:58,375 --> 00:14:02,416
An older man feels
a little more responsible.

90
00:14:05,250 --> 00:14:07,458
How are your parents
taking all of this?

91
00:14:29,166 --> 00:14:31,416
Thank you
for doing this for me.

92
00:14:32,416 --> 00:14:33,500
Of course.

93
00:14:37,166 --> 00:14:39,083
Can't she just
leave her family?

94
00:14:39,750 --> 00:14:42,166
She can't. She loves them.

95
00:14:42,250 --> 00:14:43,583
What about the truth?

96
00:14:43,666 --> 00:14:45,333
Well, sometimes the story

97
00:14:45,416 --> 00:14:47,166
we tell ourselves
becomes the truth.

98
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,458
To her parents,
you are her husband.

99
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,666
Memorize everything
in the folder.

100
00:14:53,750 --> 00:14:56,166
Every word. Every detail.

101
00:14:56,958 --> 00:14:58,250
- Okay?
- Mm-hmm.

102
00:14:58,791 --> 00:15:00,000
Okay.

103
00:17:39,875 --> 00:17:40,958
Brian?

104
00:17:45,958 --> 00:17:47,398
- Brian?
- Shit.

105
00:17:47,583 --> 00:17:48,958
Phillip?

106
00:17:49,750 --> 00:17:50,833
What's going on?

107
00:17:50,916 --> 00:17:52,416
Nothing. Just...
I need a moment.

108
00:17:52,500 --> 00:17:53,958
How long's a moment?

109
00:17:54,041 --> 00:17:55,625
A moment, you know?
A moment.

110
00:17:55,708 --> 00:17:57,166
We need you downstairs now.

111
00:17:57,708 --> 00:17:59,828
Aiko, listen. I'm sorry.
I can't go through with this.

112
00:18:02,250 --> 00:18:03,500
Listen.

113
00:18:03,583 --> 00:18:05,916
All you have to do is sip sake.

114
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:07,000
That's it.

115
00:18:07,083 --> 00:18:08,750
No. It's... It's a lie.

116
00:18:09,666 --> 00:18:11,458
I'm messing with people's lives.

117
00:18:13,125 --> 00:18:14,958
You cannot do this to me.

118
00:18:17,416 --> 00:18:19,000
- Hey.
- What are you doing?

119
00:18:19,083 --> 00:18:20,250
This is not a lie.

120
00:18:20,333 --> 00:18:21,666
It's an opportunity.

121
00:18:21,750 --> 00:18:23,625
The parents get
the memory they want.

122
00:18:23,708 --> 00:18:25,625
The bride gets her freedom.

123
00:18:25,708 --> 00:18:29,250
If you don't go through with
this, you will ruin her life.

124
00:18:29,333 --> 00:18:30,375
Do you understand?

125
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:32,791
Get out.

126
00:18:35,958 --> 00:18:37,750
Phillip.

127
00:18:37,833 --> 00:18:38,833
Come on!

128
00:18:40,416 --> 00:18:42,000
Go. Go.

129
00:19:57,916 --> 00:20:00,916
Welcome to our family, Brian.

130
00:20:14,041 --> 00:20:15,750
That was
a beautiful wedding.

131
00:20:15,833 --> 00:20:16,833
Yes.

132
00:20:23,833 --> 00:20:25,291
Nice room.

133
00:20:25,375 --> 00:20:26,541
Very.

134
00:20:34,041 --> 00:20:35,041
I got it.

135
00:21:02,916 --> 00:21:03,916
Phillip?

136
00:21:08,416 --> 00:21:09,576
Congratulations.

137
00:21:57,416 --> 00:21:59,208
I got married today, Lola.

138
00:22:02,541 --> 00:22:04,000
No, it was for work.

139
00:22:12,291 --> 00:22:14,041
Well, it was...

140
00:22:15,333 --> 00:22:18,208
It was terrifying
and exhilarating.

141
00:22:18,291 --> 00:22:22,000
And I haven't felt something
like that in a long time.

142
00:22:22,541 --> 00:22:25,875
And I know that it was fake,

143
00:22:28,500 --> 00:22:30,833
but there were moments
that it felt real.

144
00:22:51,458 --> 00:22:52,458
Already?

145
00:22:52,500 --> 00:22:54,541
Hmm.

146
00:22:55,666 --> 00:22:58,833
I give you ten more minutes.

147
00:22:59,750 --> 00:23:01,083
It's your wedding night.

148
00:23:28,750 --> 00:23:30,184
But
if you wanna keep this job,

149
00:23:30,208 --> 00:23:33,125
I need to know that you're
committed moving forward.

150
00:23:33,208 --> 00:23:35,000
No more hiding in bathrooms.

151
00:23:35,083 --> 00:23:36,625
That won't happen again.

152
00:23:36,708 --> 00:23:38,083
I am, I promise.

153
00:23:42,208 --> 00:23:44,000
- Huh?
- A father?

154
00:24:00,250 --> 00:24:01,250
Later.

155
00:24:07,916 --> 00:24:09,458
This girl needs a father

156
00:24:09,541 --> 00:24:11,791
in order to transfer
to a private school.

157
00:24:11,875 --> 00:24:13,583
You can't be a single mother?

158
00:24:13,666 --> 00:24:14,791
She's been denied once,

159
00:24:14,875 --> 00:24:16,958
and her mother
doesn't wanna risk it again.

160
00:24:17,041 --> 00:24:17,875
Oh, I get it.

161
00:24:17,958 --> 00:24:19,517
So I just play her dad
for the interview?

162
00:24:19,541 --> 00:24:20,750
Actually, no.

163
00:24:20,833 --> 00:24:22,500
The mother thinks
it'll be better

164
00:24:22,583 --> 00:24:25,041
if her daughter believes
you're her real father.

165
00:24:25,125 --> 00:24:26,375
Why?

166
00:24:26,458 --> 00:24:29,250
Well, she's been
feeling down, lately.

167
00:24:29,333 --> 00:24:31,833
And her mother's hoping
that meeting her father

168
00:24:31,916 --> 00:24:34,291
would give her
the confidence she needs.

169
00:24:34,375 --> 00:24:36,291
Also, the mother
doesn't want her daughter

170
00:24:36,375 --> 00:24:38,708
to have to pretend
during the interview.

171
00:24:38,791 --> 00:24:42,375
So, your relationship with her
has to feel authentic.

172
00:24:43,333 --> 00:24:45,208
Listen, I didn't grow up
with a father,

173
00:24:45,291 --> 00:24:47,250
so I don't really know
how to be one.

174
00:24:47,833 --> 00:24:49,333
Now is your chance.

175
00:24:52,416 --> 00:24:53,750
How long is the commitment?

176
00:24:53,833 --> 00:24:56,500
Well, you will meet with her
regularly.

177
00:24:56,583 --> 00:24:59,500
At least up till the test,
which is in three weeks.

178
00:24:59,583 --> 00:25:01,875
So, you need to
get to know her right away.

179
00:25:01,958 --> 00:25:02,958
What if she finds out?

180
00:25:03,041 --> 00:25:04,083
She can't.

181
00:25:04,791 --> 00:25:06,708
You have to trust yourself.

182
00:25:40,458 --> 00:25:41,833
Hey.

183
00:25:44,083 --> 00:25:46,041
Can you give me
just five minutes?

184
00:25:46,125 --> 00:25:47,291
Why?

185
00:25:47,375 --> 00:25:49,625
Come on. Please.

186
00:25:58,083 --> 00:25:59,184
Can I get you
something to drink?

187
00:25:59,208 --> 00:26:00,208
Nope.

188
00:26:06,833 --> 00:26:08,666
You knew the situation.

189
00:26:08,750 --> 00:26:10,125
You knew we were
her last option,

190
00:26:10,208 --> 00:26:12,083
and you still nearly backed out.

191
00:26:12,166 --> 00:26:13,875
- But I didn't.
- But you would have.

192
00:26:15,625 --> 00:26:18,041
See, you're just a...

193
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,583
You will never understand
how things work here.

194
00:26:26,750 --> 00:26:28,470
- You're right.
- I am...

195
00:26:28,541 --> 00:26:33,458
But Japan is my home now. And
I want to try to understand.

196
00:26:54,875 --> 00:26:56,541
Why do you do this?

197
00:26:56,625 --> 00:26:58,291
- What?
- This job.

198
00:26:58,375 --> 00:27:02,000
You're so passionate
about it. Why?

199
00:27:08,166 --> 00:27:10,166
It's the way
these people look at you.

200
00:27:10,916 --> 00:27:14,666
Like they've been waiting
for you their whole lives.

201
00:27:16,208 --> 00:27:18,625
Despite everything Tada says,

202
00:27:19,583 --> 00:27:21,166
these people stay with you.

203
00:27:22,791 --> 00:27:24,375
Sometimes all we need

204
00:27:24,458 --> 00:27:26,833
is someone to look us in the eye

205
00:27:26,916 --> 00:27:28,791
and remind us we exist.

206
00:28:35,916 --> 00:28:37,875
Hello there, Mia.

207
00:28:37,958 --> 00:28:40,375
My name is Kevin.
I'm your father.

208
00:28:40,958 --> 00:28:43,333
Hi, Mia. I'm your father.

209
00:28:44,833 --> 00:28:46,666
No, that's way too formal.

210
00:28:47,250 --> 00:28:51,708
Hi, Mia. You've grown so much.
Look how big you are.

211
00:28:55,250 --> 00:28:57,583
I'm Kevin. I'm your father.

212
00:29:00,458 --> 00:29:01,458
I missed you.

213
00:29:16,041 --> 00:29:17,208
Hitomi-san.

214
00:29:18,333 --> 00:29:20,750
Hi. Thank you for coming.

215
00:29:20,833 --> 00:29:22,000
Please take this.

216
00:29:22,708 --> 00:29:23,791
It's a backpack.

217
00:29:23,875 --> 00:29:25,583
She's been begging me for it.

218
00:29:26,166 --> 00:29:27,166
Perfect.

219
00:29:27,708 --> 00:29:31,833
So, she doesn't know
she's meeting you today.

220
00:29:31,916 --> 00:29:33,083
Oh.

221
00:29:33,166 --> 00:29:34,458
She wouldn't have come
otherwise.

222
00:29:35,541 --> 00:29:36,708
Okay, no problem.

223
00:29:37,583 --> 00:29:38,916
Thank you.

224
00:30:05,916 --> 00:30:07,250
Hello, Mia.

225
00:30:11,416 --> 00:30:13,333
Here. Look,
I got you something.

226
00:30:15,500 --> 00:30:16,708
I hope you like it.

227
00:30:23,625 --> 00:30:25,708
- I hate it!
- Mia!

228
00:30:25,791 --> 00:30:26,791
You can't bribe me.

229
00:30:26,875 --> 00:30:29,541
I'm sorry that
you feel that way, Mia.

230
00:30:29,625 --> 00:30:31,145
And I know
that I have not been here...

231
00:30:31,916 --> 00:30:33,166
Mia!

232
00:30:34,875 --> 00:30:35,875
Mia!

233
00:30:36,291 --> 00:30:37,666
Hey. Mia!

234
00:30:38,208 --> 00:30:39,833
Stop following me!

235
00:30:40,333 --> 00:30:41,666
I know her! Hey.

236
00:30:42,208 --> 00:30:43,208
Go away.

237
00:30:43,250 --> 00:30:45,250
Wait up.

238
00:30:45,333 --> 00:30:47,500
Please, stop. I can explain.

239
00:30:49,041 --> 00:30:50,791
Did you think
you can just show up?

240
00:30:50,875 --> 00:30:54,625
Your mom said that you need me
to get you into school.

241
00:30:54,708 --> 00:30:56,875
That's the only reason
why you're here?

242
00:30:56,958 --> 00:30:59,041
No, no, no. It's not.

243
00:30:59,125 --> 00:31:00,708
I've been wanting to see you,

244
00:31:00,791 --> 00:31:02,208
and there hasn't been a moment

245
00:31:02,291 --> 00:31:03,476
when I haven't thought
about you.

246
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:04,666
Why did you leave us, then?

247
00:31:04,750 --> 00:31:05,666
Because I was stupid.

248
00:31:05,750 --> 00:31:08,250
And I can see,
you're very angry with me.

249
00:31:09,166 --> 00:31:11,583
And you probably
shouldn't forgive me,

250
00:31:11,666 --> 00:31:13,625
but I'm here now.

251
00:31:14,875 --> 00:31:17,083
Mia.

252
00:31:22,708 --> 00:31:24,500
Yes. We need him.

253
00:31:24,583 --> 00:31:26,583
Let me be some use to you.

254
00:31:30,750 --> 00:31:31,833
Fine.

255
00:31:31,916 --> 00:31:35,041
But lock it and swear
you'll never leave us again.

256
00:31:38,875 --> 00:31:39,958
Okay.

257
00:31:40,458 --> 00:31:41,500
I... I swear.

258
00:31:53,416 --> 00:31:54,416
Sorry.

259
00:32:45,041 --> 00:32:46,500
How's it going, dad?

260
00:32:46,583 --> 00:32:47,958
She hates me.

261
00:32:48,041 --> 00:32:49,291
That's what being a parent is.

262
00:32:49,375 --> 00:32:50,666
<i>No, I am serious.</i>

263
00:32:50,750 --> 00:32:52,208
She hates me.

264
00:32:52,291 --> 00:32:53,875
<i>She doesn't hate you.</i>

265
00:32:53,958 --> 00:32:55,500
<i>She hates
the man you're playing.</i>

266
00:32:56,041 --> 00:32:59,291
Listen to what they want,
and feed them what they need.

267
00:32:59,375 --> 00:33:00,666
You're just acting.

268
00:33:01,208 --> 00:33:04,500
Acting. I know. Just acting.

269
00:33:08,291 --> 00:33:10,791
<i>Anyway,</i>
<i>I've got a new client for you.</i>

270
00:33:10,875 --> 00:33:13,250
<i>You know the actor,
Kikuo Hasegawa?</i>

271
00:33:13,333 --> 00:33:14,333
<i>Of course.</i>

272
00:33:14,416 --> 00:33:16,875
<i>Well,</i>
<i>he thinks he's been forgotten.</i>

273
00:33:16,958 --> 00:33:19,166
<i>So his daughter wants
someone to interview him</i>

274
00:33:19,250 --> 00:33:20,708
<i>to honor his legacy.</i>

275
00:34:10,750 --> 00:34:11,750
Wow.

276
00:34:46,083 --> 00:34:49,291
This is a really
impressive collection.

277
00:34:50,416 --> 00:34:53,291
Classic. Mingus,
"Myself When I am Real"?

278
00:34:53,375 --> 00:34:54,416
Do you play?

279
00:34:55,125 --> 00:34:57,458
No, I don't, unfortunately.
Um...

280
00:34:57,541 --> 00:34:59,208
But I admire.

281
00:34:59,708 --> 00:35:02,583
My father, he, uh,
he played bass.

282
00:35:19,208 --> 00:35:20,809
Never thought
of it that way before.

283
00:35:22,750 --> 00:35:23,875
Let's get

284
00:35:25,583 --> 00:35:26,833
some air.

285
00:35:27,833 --> 00:35:29,833
Okay, let's do that.

286
00:35:29,916 --> 00:35:33,000
What do you want to know?

287
00:35:33,500 --> 00:35:34,500
Everything.

288
00:35:36,083 --> 00:35:37,541
There's nobody like you.

289
00:36:16,958 --> 00:36:19,583
You can record my voice,

290
00:36:20,083 --> 00:36:21,666
but please, no video.

291
00:36:45,875 --> 00:36:48,125
- Hi, Mia.
- Thank you for being here.

292
00:36:48,875 --> 00:36:49,958
Mia.

293
00:36:50,708 --> 00:36:51,750
Sorry.

294
00:36:52,291 --> 00:36:54,166
I should be done by 1:00 p.m.

295
00:36:54,958 --> 00:36:55,958
All right.

296
00:37:21,916 --> 00:37:23,436
So what are we gonna make?

297
00:37:51,333 --> 00:37:53,125
Can you be his dad too?

298
00:37:54,208 --> 00:37:55,500
Of course.

299
00:37:59,125 --> 00:38:00,405
What... What is that?

300
00:38:04,500 --> 00:38:05,500
Okay.

301
00:38:05,583 --> 00:38:07,666
Well, you're
gonna have to show me how.

302
00:38:23,541 --> 00:38:25,125
Thanks for helping Shion.

303
00:39:16,875 --> 00:39:18,601
<i>Meet me at the karaoke box.</i>

304
00:39:18,625 --> 00:39:20,666
<i>You're going to be
a cheerleader today.</i>

305
00:39:31,166 --> 00:39:33,625
I love video games.
Yeah, count me in.

306
00:39:35,791 --> 00:39:36,833
Nice room.

307
00:39:39,791 --> 00:39:40,791
One more time.

308
00:40:14,375 --> 00:40:15,500
Yeah!

309
00:40:16,125 --> 00:40:17,166
Kaori-san.

310
00:40:18,833 --> 00:40:20,041
Right this way.

311
00:40:33,791 --> 00:40:34,625
My name is Takashi.

312
00:40:34,708 --> 00:40:36,148
Hello. How are you?
Good to meet you.

313
00:40:40,750 --> 00:40:42,541
Did you trim your beard?

314
00:40:42,625 --> 00:40:43,750
It looks good, man.

315
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:09,333
Wow!

316
00:41:11,083 --> 00:41:12,458
Well, this is amazing.

317
00:41:13,958 --> 00:41:15,083
It's cool.

318
00:41:15,833 --> 00:41:16,958
But it's fake.

319
00:41:17,041 --> 00:41:20,750
But isn't it real
to the person who made it?

320
00:41:22,291 --> 00:41:24,375
You know, sometimes
it's okay to pretend.

321
00:41:31,500 --> 00:41:32,750
I gotta take a quick call.

322
00:41:32,833 --> 00:41:34,791
- I'll be right back.
- Okay.

323
00:41:37,375 --> 00:41:38,958
- Hello?
<i>- Hey!</i>

324
00:41:39,041 --> 00:41:40,625
<i>So, you remember
the detective series</i>

325
00:41:40,708 --> 00:41:42,000
<i>you auditioned for last month?</i>

326
00:41:42,583 --> 00:41:44,666
<i>- You got the part.</i>
- Really?

327
00:41:44,750 --> 00:41:46,791
- <i>Congratulations, Phillip.</i>
- Wow.

328
00:41:46,875 --> 00:41:49,625
<i>They're shooting in Korea
and want you there right away.</i>

329
00:41:49,708 --> 00:41:51,375
<i>I am so happy for you.</i>

330
00:41:51,458 --> 00:41:52,875
<i>Well deserved.</i>

331
00:41:52,958 --> 00:41:54,750
It's good. It's great.

332
00:41:54,833 --> 00:41:57,041
<i>Oh, I have a really good
feeling about this one.</i>

333
00:41:59,125 --> 00:42:00,125
<i>Hello?</i>

334
00:42:00,625 --> 00:42:02,000
Hey, listen, um...

335
00:42:02,083 --> 00:42:04,166
I'm gonna have to go.

336
00:42:04,250 --> 00:42:05,625
Let me get back to you.
All right?

337
00:42:05,708 --> 00:42:06,916
<i>Call me back soon.</i>

338
00:42:19,625 --> 00:42:20,625
There you are.

339
00:43:34,583 --> 00:43:35,916
Are you coming?

340
00:43:37,541 --> 00:43:38,541
Yeah.

341
00:44:12,750 --> 00:44:16,458
Heaven on your tongue.

342
00:44:25,708 --> 00:44:27,541
You try.

343
00:44:46,041 --> 00:44:48,250
Is everything
all right with your daughter?

344
00:45:01,666 --> 00:45:05,583
"The man on the screen."

345
00:45:08,958 --> 00:45:10,041
Do you regret it?

346
00:45:11,291 --> 00:45:12,916
Not at the time.

347
00:45:15,166 --> 00:45:17,041
Do you have any children?

348
00:45:20,166 --> 00:45:21,250
I have a daughter.

349
00:45:25,666 --> 00:45:26,708
No.

350
00:45:27,291 --> 00:45:29,666
No. But I would like to be.

351
00:45:29,750 --> 00:45:30,916
Mmm.

352
00:45:49,708 --> 00:45:51,500
- Are you my mother?
- No.

353
00:46:18,666 --> 00:46:19,666
Oh, shit.

354
00:46:23,541 --> 00:46:25,416
Kikuo-san. Kikuo-san!

355
00:46:25,500 --> 00:46:26,559
Hey, hey! Stop, stop, stop!

356
00:46:26,583 --> 00:46:27,875
Kikuo-san!

357
00:46:27,958 --> 00:46:29,041
Hey, where are you going?

358
00:46:33,125 --> 00:46:35,458
Listen. It's me. It's John.

359
00:46:35,541 --> 00:46:36,666
We were eating together.

360
00:46:36,750 --> 00:46:39,375
And I'm writing a story
about you.

361
00:46:39,458 --> 00:46:41,583
Yeah. I think it's time
to go home.

362
00:46:43,625 --> 00:46:45,083
Yeah.

363
00:46:47,250 --> 00:46:49,666
We're gonna go in here
and get your shoes. All right?

364
00:48:02,583 --> 00:48:03,767
I can't hear you.

365
00:48:07,208 --> 00:48:08,833
So, what do you do?

366
00:48:08,916 --> 00:48:10,541
I'm a computer engineer.

367
00:48:11,083 --> 00:48:12,333
What's your nationality?

368
00:48:12,416 --> 00:48:13,458
American.

369
00:48:14,041 --> 00:48:16,000
My great-grandparents were
from Ireland.

370
00:48:16,083 --> 00:48:17,791
I'm part Irish?

371
00:48:17,875 --> 00:48:19,833
Yes, that's right.
You are.

372
00:48:19,916 --> 00:48:21,625
Wow, that's cool.

373
00:48:22,166 --> 00:48:23,458
Where were you born?

374
00:48:24,375 --> 00:48:25,625
Sit.

375
00:48:27,041 --> 00:48:29,416
Let's say this is, um,
Japan right here.

376
00:48:30,375 --> 00:48:35,166
And, over here, way over here,
this is America.

377
00:48:35,250 --> 00:48:37,083
Sort of like that.

378
00:48:37,166 --> 00:48:39,291
And right in the middle
is a place called...

379
00:48:40,916 --> 00:48:42,250
Minnesota.

380
00:48:42,333 --> 00:48:44,041
Is that
where my grandparents live?

381
00:48:44,875 --> 00:48:47,583
Uh, no. My mom did.

382
00:48:49,208 --> 00:48:51,000
My dad wasn't around that much.

383
00:48:51,958 --> 00:48:53,250
Do you talk to them?

384
00:48:54,083 --> 00:48:55,291
No. They're gone now.

385
00:48:55,958 --> 00:48:57,166
Do you have anyone left?

386
00:48:59,458 --> 00:49:00,458
I have you now.

387
00:49:04,250 --> 00:49:05,500
I have an idea.

388
00:49:06,833 --> 00:49:08,208
Type in your number.

389
00:49:09,833 --> 00:49:11,750
- Okay.
- Here. Here.

390
00:49:11,833 --> 00:49:13,250
Okay...

391
00:49:23,041 --> 00:49:25,458
♪ <i>Meow meow meow!</i> ♪

392
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:28,916
Now, I can message you.

393
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:30,416
And you won't feel alone.

394
00:49:33,791 --> 00:49:35,583
I'll race you to the sweet shop.

395
00:49:50,125 --> 00:49:51,250
Oh.

396
00:49:51,333 --> 00:49:52,375
Wow.

397
00:49:53,291 --> 00:49:55,166
- Hi.
- Hi.

398
00:50:06,666 --> 00:50:07,708
Yes.

399
00:50:13,083 --> 00:50:14,083
Mmm!

400
00:50:16,916 --> 00:50:17,916
Mia.

401
00:50:28,166 --> 00:50:29,806
You got that right.

402
00:50:46,708 --> 00:50:48,916
Well, what do I owe you?

403
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:51,000
For you, it's on the house.

404
00:50:51,083 --> 00:50:54,791
No. No, I...
I owe you, Natsumi.

405
00:50:54,875 --> 00:50:56,750
Whoa.

406
00:51:00,125 --> 00:51:01,445
- Bye.
- Bye.

407
00:51:06,916 --> 00:51:07,916
Yeah.

408
00:51:23,875 --> 00:51:26,416
"Do not open
until you get home."

409
00:51:35,791 --> 00:51:37,541
Hey, Sonia.

410
00:51:37,625 --> 00:51:39,267
<i>Hey, I was about to call you.</i>

411
00:51:39,291 --> 00:51:41,916
Listen, I... I'm gonna pass.

412
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:44,041
<i>What? Why?
You're joking, right?</i>

413
00:51:44,125 --> 00:51:45,750
No. I'm not.

414
00:51:46,250 --> 00:51:47,875
<i>I don't understand.</i>

415
00:51:47,958 --> 00:51:49,750
<i>You told me
this is what you wanted.</i>

416
00:51:49,833 --> 00:51:52,208
I know. Please tell them
that I'm very grateful,

417
00:51:52,291 --> 00:51:54,458
but I made a promise to someone

418
00:51:54,541 --> 00:51:56,166
and I need to keep it.

419
00:51:56,250 --> 00:51:57,125
<i>Phillip, you know,</i>

420
00:51:57,208 --> 00:51:58,726
<i>this could literally
change your career.</i>

421
00:51:58,750 --> 00:52:00,416
I... I can't do it.

422
00:52:00,500 --> 00:52:01,625
<i>Are you sure?</i>

423
00:52:02,750 --> 00:52:05,375
<i>I mean, you've waited
so long for this.</i>

424
00:52:06,625 --> 00:52:07,958
I know.

425
00:52:08,041 --> 00:52:09,041
I'm sorry.

426
00:52:10,250 --> 00:52:12,625
Thank you for everything
that you've done.

427
00:52:13,875 --> 00:52:14,958
We'll talk soon.

428
00:52:51,208 --> 00:52:52,625
I'm... That's... I got it...

429
00:52:59,125 --> 00:53:00,458
Hi, Mia.

430
00:53:01,166 --> 00:53:02,750
I don't wanna take the test.

431
00:53:03,375 --> 00:53:07,250
No, it... Your mom says that
it's one of the best schools

432
00:53:07,333 --> 00:53:08,333
in Japan.

433
00:53:08,416 --> 00:53:10,500
What if I get bullied?

434
00:53:10,583 --> 00:53:14,000
Well, then I will put you
in karate classes. Hi-yah!

435
00:53:14,791 --> 00:53:18,291
<i>Okay, listen,
you're gonna be great.</i>

436
00:53:18,375 --> 00:53:19,666
You're almost at the end,

437
00:53:19,750 --> 00:53:22,000
and I just know
you're gonna impress everyone.

438
00:53:22,791 --> 00:53:24,708
<i>- I hope so.</i>
- You will.

439
00:53:25,625 --> 00:53:26,958
<i>I believe in you, Mia.</i>

440
00:53:28,750 --> 00:53:30,583
<i>Thank you. See you soon.</i>

441
00:55:06,041 --> 00:55:07,291
- Shall I?
- Sure.

442
00:55:11,750 --> 00:55:14,041
Okay, there should be three
to five teachers

443
00:55:14,125 --> 00:55:15,291
at the interview.

444
00:55:15,958 --> 00:55:18,583
When you speak, hold eye contact

445
00:55:18,666 --> 00:55:20,541
for no more than five seconds.

446
00:55:21,250 --> 00:55:22,583
And our answers?

447
00:55:23,416 --> 00:55:25,291
Short and to the point.

448
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:28,750
- Should we hold hands?
- No.

449
00:55:30,125 --> 00:55:33,833
You can show some emotion,
but don't become emotional.

450
00:55:39,666 --> 00:55:40,750
Yeah.

451
00:55:40,833 --> 00:55:42,416
If they ask me,

452
00:55:46,291 --> 00:55:47,625
I answer,

453
00:55:49,208 --> 00:55:50,642
That's it? I just say, "Nothing"?

454
00:55:50,666 --> 00:55:51,666
Yes.

455
00:55:52,250 --> 00:55:53,791
The school
does not want pressure

456
00:55:53,875 --> 00:55:54,916
from the parents.

457
00:55:55,583 --> 00:55:56,916
Yeah, but it's your child.

458
00:55:57,708 --> 00:56:00,291
How long is she gonna be
going to school there for?

459
00:56:00,375 --> 00:56:02,208
Through high school for now,

460
00:56:02,291 --> 00:56:04,833
but she could go
to their university

461
00:56:04,916 --> 00:56:05,916
if she does well.

462
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:09,208
Is it normal to determine
a child's future so early?

463
00:56:09,291 --> 00:56:10,875
I'm sorry, but I didn't hire you

464
00:56:10,958 --> 00:56:13,208
to lecture me
on how to raise my child.

465
00:56:13,291 --> 00:56:14,666
I'm not trying to interfere.

466
00:56:14,750 --> 00:56:17,125
Then why are you talking
with her on the phone?

467
00:56:17,208 --> 00:56:18,791
Sending her messages?

468
00:56:18,875 --> 00:56:20,291
I'm just trying to help.

469
00:56:21,375 --> 00:56:23,125
This kid just wants
to talk to her dad.

470
00:56:25,333 --> 00:56:27,000
You are not her father.

471
00:56:29,166 --> 00:56:30,166
I know.

472
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:51,416
Do you pray?

473
00:56:52,083 --> 00:56:53,541
Not since I was 15.

474
00:56:54,041 --> 00:56:55,333
What happened?

475
00:56:55,416 --> 00:56:56,916
I turned 16.

476
00:56:59,333 --> 00:57:02,083
A little too early
to give it up.

477
00:57:06,625 --> 00:57:07,625
No.

478
00:57:09,083 --> 00:57:10,875
No, I just...
I have these memories

479
00:57:10,958 --> 00:57:13,000
of being made
to go to church, and...

480
00:57:14,041 --> 00:57:15,291
I never saw the point.

481
00:57:20,208 --> 00:57:21,934
"When in Rome,
do as Romans do."

482
00:57:21,958 --> 00:57:22,958
Mmm.

483
00:57:24,625 --> 00:57:30,458
But I also think it means
becoming more than yourself.

484
00:57:33,958 --> 00:57:36,458
Hey, um, what is in there?

485
00:57:44,583 --> 00:57:46,208
Maybe another time.

486
00:58:08,541 --> 00:58:10,375
In Amakusa.

487
00:58:11,750 --> 00:58:12,750
Why?

488
00:58:12,833 --> 00:58:15,541
I left something behind.

489
00:58:16,500 --> 00:58:18,500
And can't Masami go
and get it for you?

490
00:58:19,208 --> 00:58:23,041
Masami cannot know
that we are going.

491
00:58:23,916 --> 00:58:25,000
Why not?

492
00:58:26,666 --> 00:58:32,416
Sometimes,
all a man has are his secrets.

493
00:59:54,916 --> 00:59:55,956
Hey, it's me.

494
01:00:00,625 --> 01:00:01,625
Wow.

495
01:00:02,333 --> 01:00:03,833
How many clients have you had?

496
01:00:05,041 --> 01:00:06,625
Seven or maybe eight hundred.

497
01:00:08,666 --> 01:00:10,000
And you just keep 'em all?

498
01:00:10,541 --> 01:00:12,208
Yeah. As a reminder

499
01:00:12,291 --> 01:00:14,083
of how many people need
our help.

500
01:00:18,375 --> 01:00:19,615
It's growing on me.

501
01:00:21,291 --> 01:00:22,791
You're good at it.

502
01:00:22,875 --> 01:00:24,125
Thank you.

503
01:00:24,833 --> 01:00:26,583
It hasn't gotten too personal?

504
01:00:28,458 --> 01:00:29,458
No.

505
01:00:30,958 --> 01:00:32,041
I don't think so.

506
01:00:32,125 --> 01:00:34,208
Well, the little girl's
mother called.

507
01:00:34,791 --> 01:00:35,791
Yeah?

508
01:00:36,291 --> 01:00:38,208
She wants the next session
to be your last.

509
01:00:38,291 --> 01:00:39,291
What?

510
01:00:42,791 --> 01:00:43,791
Why?

511
01:00:43,875 --> 01:00:45,916
She's getting
a little too attached.

512
01:00:47,208 --> 01:00:48,791
What am I supposed to tell her?

513
01:00:48,875 --> 01:00:50,625
That you have to go back
to the States.

514
01:00:50,708 --> 01:00:52,208
That you will miss her.

515
01:00:53,125 --> 01:00:54,500
Just like that?

516
01:00:54,583 --> 01:00:57,000
That's how this business works.

517
01:00:57,083 --> 01:00:59,000
All relationships have to end.

518
01:00:59,833 --> 01:01:00,916
Then what?

519
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:02,375
We move on.

520
01:01:02,458 --> 01:01:04,291
There's always someone new.

521
01:01:05,875 --> 01:01:07,208
You'll get used to it.

522
01:01:11,083 --> 01:01:13,083
Okay. Yeah.

523
01:01:14,833 --> 01:01:16,250
Yeah.

524
01:01:33,541 --> 01:01:35,083
Hello.

525
01:01:35,166 --> 01:01:36,166
Hey, John.

526
01:01:37,583 --> 01:01:38,583
What's all this?

527
01:01:48,333 --> 01:01:51,500
Hey, listen. I can't take you.

528
01:01:52,125 --> 01:01:53,791
Sure you can.

529
01:01:56,291 --> 01:01:58,041
What if something happens
to you?

530
01:01:59,833 --> 01:02:03,083
Aren't you a writer?

531
01:02:04,333 --> 01:02:05,416
I am.

532
01:02:05,500 --> 01:02:10,125
Then how can you write my story

533
01:02:10,208 --> 01:02:16,375
if you don't start
at the beginning?

534
01:02:18,750 --> 01:02:20,750
Your daughter wants you to stay.

535
01:02:37,333 --> 01:02:38,333
I'll...

536
01:02:39,166 --> 01:02:41,041
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- No.

537
01:03:34,333 --> 01:03:35,773
Did you study the notes?

538
01:03:36,208 --> 01:03:37,208
Got it.

539
01:03:38,500 --> 01:03:39,833
Do you have any questions?

540
01:03:40,458 --> 01:03:41,541
I'm good.

541
01:03:41,625 --> 01:03:42,708
Okay.

542
01:03:44,333 --> 01:03:45,916
Mia, are you okay?

543
01:03:48,750 --> 01:03:51,916
- I think so.
- Hey. You got this.

544
01:03:53,041 --> 01:03:54,500
You're gonna do great.

545
01:04:18,625 --> 01:04:19,625
Kevin.

546
01:04:19,708 --> 01:04:20,708
No, look, just...

547
01:04:26,916 --> 01:04:28,000
See?

548
01:04:28,791 --> 01:04:30,791
- She's very talented.
- Right?

549
01:04:31,791 --> 01:04:33,625
- Thank you.
- Okay.

550
01:04:44,666 --> 01:04:46,083
Okay.

551
01:04:46,166 --> 01:04:47,642
- Which one is it?
- Honest communication.

552
01:04:47,666 --> 01:04:50,041
Sorry. Americans,
we talk before we think.

553
01:04:55,583 --> 01:04:57,875
Mia has a lot
of individual personality.

554
01:04:57,958 --> 01:05:00,125
Do you think she will
get along with other students?

555
01:05:00,208 --> 01:05:01,916
Individual personality?

556
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:03,708
We want our students
to excel on their own,

557
01:05:03,791 --> 01:05:05,591
but we need to know
they can work with others.

558
01:05:05,666 --> 01:05:08,291
She has plenty of friends
at her current school.

559
01:05:08,375 --> 01:05:10,625
And she's very thoughtful.

560
01:05:10,708 --> 01:05:13,833
She asked me to be a father
to a little boy

561
01:05:13,916 --> 01:05:16,500
whose parents didn't come
to the class visitations.

562
01:05:32,458 --> 01:05:35,666
Yes,
and if you should choose

563
01:05:35,750 --> 01:05:38,291
to accept our daughter,

564
01:05:39,500 --> 01:05:42,250
please be there for her.

565
01:05:43,583 --> 01:05:47,666
She needs to dream big,
and she needs to be unafraid.

566
01:05:47,750 --> 01:05:50,375
She makes me a better person
every day.

567
01:05:50,458 --> 01:05:53,833
And I'm sure that

568
01:05:53,916 --> 01:05:55,541
she will make this
a better school.

569
01:05:59,625 --> 01:06:00,958
Okay, thank you.

570
01:06:23,166 --> 01:06:24,166
Thank you.

571
01:06:30,958 --> 01:06:32,916
Can we have dinner together?

572
01:06:35,833 --> 01:06:37,833
Mia, he can't.

573
01:06:39,833 --> 01:06:41,250
Why?

574
01:06:41,333 --> 01:06:43,083
I have to go back to America.

575
01:06:45,125 --> 01:06:46,208
For how long?

576
01:06:48,500 --> 01:06:52,000
A year, maybe longer.

577
01:06:52,625 --> 01:06:54,041
But you just got here.

578
01:06:55,708 --> 01:06:56,750
I know.

579
01:06:57,333 --> 01:06:58,958
You work from here?

580
01:06:59,041 --> 01:07:01,041
My friend's dad works from home.

581
01:07:01,125 --> 01:07:02,208
I can't.

582
01:07:03,541 --> 01:07:04,625
They need me there.

583
01:07:06,583 --> 01:07:07,833
You'll be back, right?

584
01:07:15,208 --> 01:07:17,458
I want you to know
how proud I am of you.

585
01:07:19,625 --> 01:07:22,041
I'm gonna need you
to be strong for your mom.

586
01:07:22,750 --> 01:07:23,750
Can you do that?

587
01:07:31,625 --> 01:07:32,916
I'll miss you, Dad.

588
01:07:35,791 --> 01:07:36,791
Mia?

589
01:07:44,250 --> 01:07:45,500
Take care, Hitomi.

590
01:08:10,583 --> 01:08:12,166
I'm really gonna miss that kid.

591
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:15,083
Her mom did
what she thought was best.

592
01:08:17,500 --> 01:08:18,500
Yeah.

593
01:08:21,875 --> 01:08:23,458
Would you ever use our service?

594
01:08:24,083 --> 01:08:25,750
- You mean hire someone?
- Mm-hmm.

595
01:08:27,041 --> 01:08:28,375
Never thought of that.

596
01:08:30,208 --> 01:08:31,666
Well, if you could hire someone

597
01:08:31,750 --> 01:08:34,208
to play someone in your life,

598
01:08:34,708 --> 01:08:35,875
who would that be?

599
01:08:35,958 --> 01:08:37,791
- You're being serious?
- Yeah.

600
01:08:42,625 --> 01:08:43,625
My mom.

601
01:08:44,416 --> 01:08:45,416
Why?

602
01:08:46,541 --> 01:08:48,541
Because she never judged me.

603
01:08:49,291 --> 01:08:51,708
And it would be nice
to feel that again.

604
01:08:57,500 --> 01:08:58,500
Who would you choose?

605
01:08:59,166 --> 01:09:00,166
Me?

606
01:09:01,625 --> 01:09:03,875
- I don't know.
- Come on, don't give me that.

607
01:09:05,166 --> 01:09:06,166
I don't.

608
01:09:08,958 --> 01:09:11,625
Well, at least tell me
what happened here.

609
01:09:11,708 --> 01:09:15,791
Were you in an underground
Tokyo fight club?

610
01:09:17,791 --> 01:09:19,291
I wish, I mean...

611
01:09:21,375 --> 01:09:23,000
Angry housewife.

612
01:09:23,583 --> 01:09:24,666
It was for a job?

613
01:09:26,416 --> 01:09:27,583
You tell Tada?

614
01:09:29,291 --> 01:09:30,291
Yeah.

615
01:09:31,125 --> 01:09:32,708
It comes with the territory.

616
01:09:35,041 --> 01:09:38,791
You know apologies are
our most popular service.

617
01:09:43,291 --> 01:09:44,583
I'm probably the last person

618
01:09:44,666 --> 01:09:46,416
you should ask for advice from,

619
01:09:46,500 --> 01:09:49,000
but if you ever need someone
to talk to...

620
01:09:52,458 --> 01:09:53,541
Thanks.

621
01:11:53,416 --> 01:11:55,000
Kikuo-san, psst, hey.

622
01:11:55,083 --> 01:11:56,583
Kikuo-san, wake up.

623
01:11:57,708 --> 01:11:59,291
- John.
- You ready?

624
01:11:59,875 --> 01:12:00,916
For what?

625
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:02,166
Jailbreak.

626
01:12:02,250 --> 01:12:03,541
Jailbreak.

627
01:12:03,625 --> 01:12:04,625
Yeah. Here.

628
01:12:04,708 --> 01:12:05,875
Put this on.

629
01:12:07,500 --> 01:12:08,916
What is this?

630
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:11,416
It's your disguise. Go ahead.

631
01:12:11,500 --> 01:12:12,750
Terrible.

632
01:12:12,833 --> 01:12:17,125
I choose my own costume.

633
01:12:19,916 --> 01:12:24,625
♪ <i>Now, I'm wakin'</i>
<i>At the crack of dawn </i> ♪

634
01:12:25,125 --> 01:12:28,500
♪ <i>To send</i>
<i>A little money home </i> ♪

635
01:12:28,583 --> 01:12:32,458
♪ <i>From here to the moon </i> ♪

636
01:12:32,541 --> 01:12:35,791
♪ <i>Is risin' like</i>
<i>A discotheque </i> ♪

637
01:12:40,458 --> 01:12:41,458
Go!

638
01:12:41,958 --> 01:12:44,083
♪ <i>Lookin' at happiness </i> ♪

639
01:12:44,166 --> 01:12:46,041
♪ <i>Keepin' my flavor fresh </i> ♪

640
01:12:46,125 --> 01:12:48,375
♪ <i>Nobody knows I guess... </i> ♪

641
01:12:52,833 --> 01:12:56,625
♪ <i>Leavin' at six o'clock</i>
<i>Meet in a parkin' lot </i> ♪

642
01:12:56,708 --> 01:12:59,000
♪ <i>Harriet Hendershot </i> ♪

643
01:12:59,083 --> 01:13:03,958
♪ <i>Sunglasses on</i>
<i>She waits by this </i> ♪

644
01:13:04,041 --> 01:13:10,375
<i>♪ Glass and concrete
And stone ♪</i>

645
01:13:10,458 --> 01:13:14,125
<i>♪ It is just a house... ♪</i>

646
01:13:29,791 --> 01:13:30,791
Hmm.

647
01:14:04,416 --> 01:14:05,916
Kikuo-san.

648
01:15:37,708 --> 01:15:40,000
Japan has more
gods than vending machines.

649
01:19:50,416 --> 01:19:51,791
Kikuo-san.

650
01:19:58,500 --> 01:19:59,625
Kikuo-san.

651
01:20:07,583 --> 01:20:09,333
Kikuo-san!

652
01:20:14,083 --> 01:20:15,500
Kikuo-san!

653
01:20:42,500 --> 01:20:43,750
What are you doing?

654
01:20:55,791 --> 01:20:57,541
Okay. It's okay.

655
01:21:09,416 --> 01:21:10,416
What is...

656
01:21:36,458 --> 01:21:38,750
My life

657
01:21:38,833 --> 01:21:43,041
before... my life.

658
01:22:57,333 --> 01:22:58,708
Is that you?

659
01:23:55,375 --> 01:23:56,375
You good?

660
01:24:14,333 --> 01:24:15,916
Hey, I need to make a call.

661
01:24:16,916 --> 01:24:18,166
So, I'll...

662
01:24:25,750 --> 01:24:27,590
- Hey. Um...
<i>- Where are you?</i>

663
01:24:29,000 --> 01:24:30,708
- I'm in Amakusa.
- <i>What? Where?</i>

664
01:24:30,791 --> 01:24:32,458
I'm with Kikuo. He's fine.

665
01:24:32,541 --> 01:24:35,583
How can you be so stupid?
You kidnapped our client!

666
01:24:35,666 --> 01:24:38,000
- I didn't kidnap him.
- <i>You took him from his home.</i>

667
01:24:38,083 --> 01:24:40,003
No, he asked for something,
and I gave it to him.

668
01:24:40,083 --> 01:24:42,083
Isn't...
Isn't that what we do?

669
01:24:42,166 --> 01:24:43,166
Fulfillment.

670
01:24:43,250 --> 01:24:44,750
It wasn't your choice to make.

671
01:24:44,833 --> 01:24:45,750
No, it was his.

672
01:24:45,833 --> 01:24:48,541
If one word of this gets out,
my business is gone.

673
01:24:48,625 --> 01:24:50,541
- <i>Do you understand that?</i>
- You're a hypocrite.

674
01:24:50,625 --> 01:24:52,125
You talk about helping people,

675
01:24:52,208 --> 01:24:53,666
and you act like
you're saving them

676
01:24:53,750 --> 01:24:55,125
when you're actually
hurting them.

677
01:24:55,208 --> 01:24:57,528
- What are you talking about?
<i>- Aiko, the bruise on her face.</i>

678
01:24:57,583 --> 01:24:58,583
Now, that's on you.

679
01:24:59,083 --> 01:25:00,166
<i>How dare you.</i>

680
01:25:01,166 --> 01:25:03,875
Kikuo-san. Kikuo. Kikuo.

681
01:25:03,958 --> 01:25:05,541
Kikuo. Kikuo-san.

682
01:25:05,625 --> 01:25:07,791
Hey, hey, hey. Kikuo-san.

683
01:25:08,583 --> 01:25:09,666
Fuck.

684
01:25:10,458 --> 01:25:11,458
Kikuo-san.

685
01:25:13,875 --> 01:25:14,708
Kikuo-san.

686
01:31:04,125 --> 01:31:05,166
Mia.

687
01:33:33,416 --> 01:33:34,916
You look like shit.

688
01:33:37,958 --> 01:33:39,583
Hey, thanks for getting me out.

689
01:33:40,625 --> 01:33:41,791
It wasn't just me.

690
01:33:45,375 --> 01:33:46,583
What did Kikuo say?

691
01:33:47,458 --> 01:33:49,833
That he forced you
to be his accomplice.

692
01:33:49,916 --> 01:33:51,833
He did?

693
01:33:51,916 --> 01:33:54,416
And he told Masami-san
to drop the charges.

694
01:34:00,500 --> 01:34:01,625
So why did you do it?

695
01:34:04,250 --> 01:34:05,333
I needed to help him.

696
01:34:08,583 --> 01:34:09,958
But why take the risk?

697
01:34:16,541 --> 01:34:17,791
Um...

698
01:34:22,375 --> 01:34:24,000
My father died two years ago.

699
01:34:26,000 --> 01:34:27,458
And, um...

700
01:34:30,291 --> 01:34:31,875
I didn't go to the funeral.

701
01:34:37,458 --> 01:34:39,958
Got on a train
and went to the airport...

702
01:34:42,916 --> 01:34:46,125
I just...
just sat in the terminal.

703
01:34:59,375 --> 01:35:00,791
So I wanted to be there
for Kikuo.

704
01:35:59,083 --> 01:36:00,083
Hey.

705
01:37:15,625 --> 01:37:17,833
I will
see you again, my friend.

706
01:38:26,500 --> 01:38:27,958
Did you say goodbye?

707
01:38:29,083 --> 01:38:30,208
Yeah, I did.

708
01:38:34,458 --> 01:38:36,166
I am sorry for what I said.

709
01:38:37,250 --> 01:38:38,416
I needed to hear it.

710
01:38:40,875 --> 01:38:41,958
Come on.

711
01:39:51,541 --> 01:39:52,750
Hey, Mia.

712
01:39:53,625 --> 01:39:56,500
Congratulations on
getting into school.

713
01:40:06,750 --> 01:40:08,500
Is my mom paying you?

714
01:40:09,041 --> 01:40:13,208
No. But I asked her
if I could visit you.

715
01:40:13,291 --> 01:40:14,625
Why are you here?

716
01:40:16,333 --> 01:40:17,458
I'm just here to talk.

717
01:40:17,541 --> 01:40:19,000
I don't talk to strangers.

718
01:40:19,541 --> 01:40:21,083
I can go, if you want.

719
01:40:23,916 --> 01:40:26,750
Why do adults always lie?

720
01:40:30,083 --> 01:40:32,791
It's because it's a lot easier
than telling the truth.

721
01:40:33,916 --> 01:40:35,416
Sometimes they lie

722
01:40:35,500 --> 01:40:37,916
to protect the people
that they care about,

723
01:40:38,000 --> 01:40:41,041
but your mom never wanted
to hurt you.

724
01:40:41,583 --> 01:40:43,541
You hurt me too.

725
01:40:43,625 --> 01:40:45,041
And you promised you wouldn't.

726
01:40:45,125 --> 01:40:46,208
I know.

727
01:40:46,833 --> 01:40:48,875
I know. And I'm sorry.

728
01:40:49,416 --> 01:40:50,875
We should've been
honest with you.

729
01:41:01,125 --> 01:41:02,333
It's not fair.

730
01:41:05,166 --> 01:41:06,750
I liked you being my dad.

731
01:41:08,250 --> 01:41:09,333
Me too.

732
01:41:12,583 --> 01:41:16,833
You know, you could have
told me you were famous.

733
01:41:16,916 --> 01:41:18,750
I'm not famous.

734
01:41:23,583 --> 01:41:24,750
What's your real name?

735
01:41:27,666 --> 01:41:28,875
I'm Phillip.

736
01:41:34,500 --> 01:41:35,541
I'm Mia.

737
01:41:51,750 --> 01:41:55,291
Where... And how did you
get on that TV show?

738
01:41:55,375 --> 01:41:57,125
How'd I get on a TV show?

